    {
      "id": "APP2",
      "title": "Appendix 2: Withholding or Ceasing Resuscitation",
      "icon": "🛑",
      "type": "text",
      "sections": [
        {"heading": "Withholding Resuscitation", "content": "The following are reasons to withhold resuscitation."},
        {"heading": "Advance Care Directive", "content": "An advance care directive that states that CPR be withheld. Refer to Appendix 3: Advance care directive and end-of-life care."},
        {"heading": "Obvious Death", "content": "Resuscitation may be withheld where there is obvious death or death has been verified by a registered medical practitioner, registered nurse, or registered paramedic.\n\nSigns of obvious death: rigor mortis, postmortem lividity, putrefaction/decomposition, injuries incompatible with life (e.g. decapitation, incineration, cranial and cerebral destruction, hemicorporectomy combined with absence of signs of life)."},
        {"heading": "Ceasing Resuscitation", "content": "Resuscitation may be ceased where the scene is unsafe.\n\nWhere possible, a registered paramedic, registered nurse or registered medical practitioner should decide when resuscitation efforts are to be ceased. If unavailable, NEPT crews may consult with the provider clinician or AV clinician.\n\nFactors that may prompt consultation for cessation:\n- Crew exhaustion\n- Prolonged resuscitation (>45 minutes) with initial rhythm non-shockable (asystole/no shock advised)"}
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "APP3",
      "title": "Appendix 3: Advance Care Directives & End-of-Life Care",
      "icon": "📋",
      "type": "text",
      "sections": [
        {"heading": "Overview", "content": "High-quality end-of-life care relies on open communication, informed decision-making and collaboration among healthcare providers, families and carers - including the NEPT sector in Victoria."},
        {"heading": "Advance Care Directive (ACD)", "content": "NEPT crew members may provide or withhold treatment based on an ACD if the documentation is sighted or accepted in good faith. Details of any decisions made based on the ACD must be documented in the NEPT patient care record."},
        {"heading": "IFT & Facility-to-Home Transfers", "content": "NEPT crew members must request a copy of any ACD before commencing transport from a health facility. The ACD must be included in the patient care record. Where a copy is not obtained, advise the sending facility that NEPT will treat according to CPPs if necessary."},
        {"heading": "Home-to-Facility Transfers", "content": "Documentation may be sighted or accepted in good faith. If unavailable, record full details of information given and the person providing it. If in doubt about the patient's wishes, the default position is to treat as appropriate."},
        {"heading": "Palliative Patients", "content": "Palliative care patients with a pre-existing terminal illness and not for advanced life support may still be transported by NEPT, provided the ACD is sighted. If the patient dies in transit (and a decision not to treat/resuscitate has been documented), contact the AV Clinician for advice."},
        {"heading": "Instructional vs Values Directives", "content": "Instructional directive: patient may consent to or refuse a specific medical treatment - must be complied with.\n\nValues directive: patient makes general statements about preferences and values.\n\nRefusal of treatment certificates made prior to 12 March 2018 are treated as instructional directives."},
        {"heading": "Medical Treatment Decision Maker Priority", "content": "If an adult lacks decision-making capacity, the medical treatment decision maker represents the patient. Priority order:\n1. Appointed medical treatment decision maker\n2. VCAT-appointed guardian\n3. Spouse or domestic partner\n4. Primary carer\n5. Adult child\n6. Parent\n7. Adult sibling\n\nFor children: parent, guardian or person with parental responsibility."}
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "APP4",
      "title": "Appendix 4: Mental Health Patients",
      "icon": "🧠",
      "type": "text",
      "sections": [
        {"heading": "Key Message", "content": "The Mental Health and Wellbeing Act 2022 aims to ensure assessment and treatment of persons with mental illness are provided in the least restrictive way possible. NEPT services are NOT authorised to administer sedation for transport of mental health patients; however may transport patients who have already received sedation provided they are suitable for NEPT."},
        {"heading": "Authorised Persons", "content": "Under the Mental Health and Wellbeing Act 2022, authorised persons are: registered paramedics working for AV, police officers, PSOs, registered medical practitioners employed by a designated mental health service, and authorised mental health practitioners (registered psychologist, registered nurse, social worker, or registered occupational therapist employed by a designated mental health service)."},
        {"heading": "Bodily Restraint", "content": "Authorised persons may use bodily restraint only if:\n- All reasonable less restrictive options have been tried or considered unsuitable\n- The restraint is necessary to prevent serious and imminent harm to the person or another person\n\nThe use of bodily restraint must be documented in accordance with organisational records management practices."},
        {"heading": "Searches for Safe Transport", "content": "Authorised persons may search a person in their care if they reasonably suspect the person is carrying something that presents a danger to health and safety. Before searching, the authorised person must explain the purpose and seek cooperation. The search must be: conducted with reasonable privacy, as quickly as practicable, by least invasive method practicable."},
        {"heading": "Sedation for Safe Transport", "content": "Sedation is a form of chemical restraint under the Act. A registered medical practitioner can administer (or direct a registered nurse or AV paramedic to administer) sedation only if:\n- All reasonable less restrictive options have been tried or considered unsuitable\n- Sedation is necessary to prevent serious and imminent harm\n\nMust be documented by both the prescribing and administering person."}
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "APP5",
      "title": "Appendix 5: Double-Loading (Low Acuity Only)",
      "icon": "🚑",
      "type": "text",
      "sections": [
        {"heading": "Definition", "content": "Double-loading: 2 patients requiring clinical transport in a single vehicle. Only patients classified as low acuity may be double-loaded. Low acuity: does not require active management or invasive/continuous monitoring, no deterioration forecast, and assessed as likely haemodynamically stable for the duration of transport."},
        {"heading": "Conditions Preventing Double-Loading", "content": "Even if otherwise low acuity, double-loading is prevented if:\n- Patient is behaving in a way that may distress or endanger the other patient\n- Patient is immune-suppressed\n- Patient has a condition likely to cause offence or distress\n- Patient is at high risk of dying during transport (e.g. palliative)\n- Patient has or is suspected of having an infectious disease with high transmission risk\n- Patient reasonably requires privacy due to medical condition\n- Patient requires therapeutic or monitoring devices that prevent ready access"},
        {"heading": "Supervision Requirement", "content": "A suitably qualified NEPT crew member must remain with the patient during transport. Patients must not be left unattended in the patient compartment. Transport time = time of receiving handover at sending facility until handover at receiving facility or destination."}
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "APP6",
      "title": "Appendix 6: Minimum Equipment List",
      "icon": "🧰",
      "type": "equipment_text",
      "sections": [
        {"heading": "Regulatory Requirement", "content": "The regulations prescribe that a licence holder operating a NEPT vehicle must have all equipment and supplies necessary to meet the patient's clinical needs for the duration of transport. This includes (but is not limited to) an AED, oxygen, suction and a BVM. The NEPT licence holder is responsible for ensuring equipment is present, maintained and calibrated per manufacturer's instructions."},
        {"heading": "Low Acuity", "content": "AED, BVM (adult & paediatric, multiple face mask sizes), Arterial tourniquet(s), Shears, Pulse oximetry, Thermometer, Sphygmomanometer (small adult/paediatric, normal, bariatric cuffs), Oxygen (portable & in vehicle), Linen, Hudson O2 mask (paediatric & adult), Nasal cannula O2, Infectious disease PPE (gloves, gown, glasses, surgical mask, P2 mask), Suction (in vehicle) with Yankauer, Emesis bags, Infection waste bags, Vehicle cleaning equipment, Spill kit, GPS/mobile phone mount, Soft C-collars, Sharps container, Manual handling equipment (slide sheet etc.), Bed pan, SHEMP equipment (high-vis vests, helmets etc.), Glucometer, Oropharyngeal airway, Alcohol swabs/wipes\n\nFirst Aid Kit: Gauze, Combine dressings, CAT tourniquet, Roller bandages, Triangular bandages, Saline (NaCl), Lifting cushion\n\nMedicines - PTO: Adrenaline auto-injector, Aspirin, Paracetamol, Salbutamol pMDI, Glucose paste"},
        {"heading": "Medium Acuity (all of low acuity plus)", "content": "Cardiac monitor (3/5 lead minimum), ECG dots, Manual defibrillator with spare pads (paediatric & adult), Suction catheter incl. Y-suction catheter 6fr-14fr, SGA/LMA, NRB mask (paediatric & adult), NEB mask (paediatric & adult), Portable suction, Pelvic binder, Formable splint, Stethoscope, 1ml syringe with IM needles\n\nMedicines - ATA/EN: Methoxyflurane and/or Entonox, Glyceryl trinitrate, Glucagon, Adrenaline 1:1000 and/or autoinjector, Ondansetron (wafers), Ipratropium bromide poly-ampoule, Salbutamol poly-ampoule"},
        {"heading": "High Acuity (all of medium acuity plus)", "content": "12-lead capable ECG, Syringe driver(s), Arterial pressure bag, Arterial forceps, IV pole and attachment point, Arterial line transducer set and cable/s, ETCO2 filter line (adult), PEEP valve(s), Consumables for IVC and medicine/infusion administration (giving sets), 50ml syringes (infusions), 20ml syringes, 10ml syringes, Normal saline IV bags\n\nMedicines - RNCC: Metaraminol, Atropine, Amiodarone, Adrenaline 1:1000 or 1:10000, Ondansetron (ampoule IV/IM), D10W, D5W (infusion dilutant)"}
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "APP7",
      "title": "Appendix 7: Prolonged Transport",
      "icon": "🕐",
      "type": "text",
      "sections": [
        {"heading": "Overview", "content": "NEPT services may provide patient care of a prolonged nature due to transport destinations, extended off-load times, and multiple episodes of care (e.g. multiple IFT transports). In addition to routine monitoring, the longer-term needs of the patient must be considered."},
        {"heading": "Long-Term Patient Needs", "content": "Consider: hydration (oral fluids), last meal / timeframe before next meal, toileting needs, repositioning, patient's own regular medication.\n\nIt is acceptable to delay transport to facilitate these needs. Request information on long-term needs during handover, including modifications (e.g. soft diet). Document on the patient care record."},
        {"heading": "Pressure Injuries", "content": "Risk factors: immobility, lack of sensory perception, poor nutrition/hydration, excess moisture or dryness, poor skin integrity, reduced blood flow, limited alertness, muscle spasms. Even short durations of stasis may cause or contribute to a pressure injury. Bariatric patients present increased risk."},
        {"heading": "Repositioning", "content": "Repositioning must occur at a minimum of every 2 hours. Document any existing pressure injury or screening on the patient care record."},
        {"heading": "Braden Scale - Pressure Injury Risk", "content": "Scores range from 6-23; lower scores indicate greater risk.\n\nVery High Risk: 9 or less\nHigh Risk: 10-12\nModerate Risk: 13-14\nMild Risk: 15-18\nNo Risk: 19-23\n\nFactors scored: sensory perception, moisture, activity, mobility, nutrition, friction and shear."}
      ]
    },
